ocacy have moved their discipline into the mainstream of academia—converse on the intellectual and personal roads they have traveled in becoming leaders in their areas of expertise. Through their thoughtful and candid recollections of the challenges they faced in becoming accepted academics, they retell the story of how the study of the Jews and Judaism in the United States rose from being long dismissed as an amateurish enterprise not worthy of serious consideration in the world of ideas to its position today as a respected field in communication with all humanities scholars. They also imagine and chart the direction the writing on American Jews will take in the coming era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHistoriansxJewszUnited States. 0aJewish historianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aJewszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aAntler, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshton, Dianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauman, Mark K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDash Moore, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiner, Hasia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGurock, Jeffrey S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGurock, Jeffrey S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLederhendler, Eli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNadell, Pamela S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrell, Riv–Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSarna, Jonathan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz, Shuly Rubin, econtributor.4ctb